  "prompt": "How many times a second does a hummingbird flap its wings?",
  "response": "Hummingbirds are renowned for their incredibly rapid wing movements, which enable their unique ability to hover in place and perform agile maneuvers. On average, hummingbirds flap their wings approximately **50 to 80 times per second**. This high wingbeat frequency varies depending on the species, size of the bird, and its activity:\n\n- **Hovering:** When maintaining a stationary position in the air, most hummingbirds flap their wings around 50 times per second.\n- **Mating Displays or Aggressive Maneuvers:** During displays or territorial disputes, some species can increase their wingbeat rate to up to 80 times per second or even slightly higher.\n\nThis rapid flapping is powered by their exceptional muscle structure and metabolism, allowing hummingbirds to sustain such high activity levels despite their small size. Additionally, their unique ball-and-socket joint at the shoulder allows their wings to rotate 180 degrees in all directions, contributing to their remarkable flight capabilities.",
